review_blob:
A nice, fresh american pale. The aroma is rich with intense pine and resiny hop character, with a hint of sweet malt. The beer is a rich orange copper color, and pours cloudy, with tiny hop flakes occasionally lifted by the carbonation. The flavor profile is intensely hoppy, with a wealth of pine hop flavor and bitterness to match, lasting into the finish. There is some light caramel malt present but the balance is definitely to the hops. The mouthfeel is modest, without much creaminess but abundant carbonation is present. The finish is slightly bitter but not astringent. All in all, it tastes like a very fresh and good american pale ale homebrew.

The pint sized cans are a novelty, but the batch i purposed were befouled with a black mildew that easily wiped off. Unsure if this is related to Hurricane Ike or not.
beer_name: Southern Star Pine Belt Pale Ale

review_blob: It is what it is... grassy aroma, yellow gold in color, easy drinking if unimaginative lager beer. Something more complex might blend better with the spicey indian/middle eastern fare it is typically served with, but are often unavailable...
On tap at the Gingerman, Fabulously hoppy, with strong American hop aroma and flavor of rich pine resins, with decent malt backing. Brilliant golden amber color, good clarity, easy drinking.

An interesting find at Massawa on Haight st in San Francisco. The beer pictured and described appears to be "Harar Light" ... there is also a Harar Dark. Only had time to sample one. Beer is imported via Oakland so perhaps that contributed to this beers freshness. Lager was a hazy golden, with fruity aroma and light creamy head. Beer was easy to drink with complex fruit ester character of banana and citrus and light malt backing. Finish was clean. More enjoyable than most reviews here would lead you to believe.

Strong IPA from Stone, obtained from a small liqour store on Haight in San Francisco. Aroma is a mixture of toast and pine. Strikes the pallet with piney hop bitterness backed by a slight but definite caramel / toffee malt presence and hints of complex alcohols. Overall, a strong double IPA.

Had on draft at Cha Cha Chas on Haight in San Francisco. A terrific surprise, with strong citusy hop aroma, hazy gold in appearance. The flavor is dominated by grapefruit and other citrus with a decent malt balance. Tastes fresh and very strongly hopped, a joy to consume.

Picked up in Williamsburg at the Cheese Shop, this IPA poured a nice golden amber color, clear, with a persistent cream colored head which laced the glass. The aroma was predominantly of piney resins and faint malt character. The flavor was dominated by the hop resin character, lots of pine, with a light malt backing. Easy to drink, smooth on the palate with a residual bitterness. Overall, a good, clean IPA.

Aroma is noticeable for a toasted biscut quality with massive floral hop character. The beer pours as a rich, inky darkness with a small but persistant tan head which leaves a trail of lace on the glass. Flavor is rich and malty, with plenty of roast and coffee character and a massive hop presence. Smooth and creamy, with a slight hint of astringency and alcoholic bite. The finish is roasty and coats the tounge. An excellent imperial stout

Aroma is a mixture of yeastiness and grass, with some hop aroma. The beer pours a golden yellow, remarkable for the intensity of the haze, even with a gentle pour. Large yeast pellet in the bottom of the bottle. Flavor is marked by predominant banana esters, some phenolic overtones and a marked yeast component. Hop bitterness seems out of balance with a pine resin predominance. Beer is way overcarbonated, with a large persistent white head. Mouthfeel consists of marked carbonation, light body. Overall, a somewhat flawed wheat. Would like to try on tap or a different bottle/batch.

beer_brewer_name: Old Dominion Brewing Company (Coastal Brewing Co.)
review_blob: Picked this up in Williamsburg, never had it before. Aroma consisted mostly of coffee with a toasty note. A light hint of vanilla in the nose. Appearance was rich and dark, as a stout should be, with a minimal tan head which quickly dissipated. Flavor was a nice balance of chocolate, with some oak and vanilla noticeable. The vanilla continues into the finish and lingers with a slight hint of astringency from the roasted malts. Hops are present, but not overassertive. Mouthfeel is modest, considering this is a stout. Leaves a bit of a roast vanilla coating on the mouth and tounge. An enjoyable stout, definitely a pleasant surprise.
